Lowriders were born in postwar California, built by working-class communities who turned secondhand Chevys into moving art, challenged state laws that tried to erase them, and created a car culture that spread from Los Angeles to Japan.
After World War II, California became the center of car customization. Returning soldiers and young mechanics had access to affordable cars and began experimenting with style and performance. In East Los Angeles, lowering a car became a statement of pride and creativity. â€œLow and slowâ€ replaced â€œfast and loud,â€ turning the car into a reflection of identity and neighborhood pride.
In 1958, California passed Vehicle Code 24008, making it illegal for any part of a carâ€™s body to sit lower than the bottom of its wheel rims. Police used the law to target lowered cars, but builders like Ron Aguirre and Jim Logue found a solution. They used surplus aircraft hydraulics from World War II to design systems that could raise or lower a car with a switch. That invention turned lowriding into both engineering and resistance.
By the 1960s and 70s, car clubs like the Imperials, Dukes, Lifestyle, and Groupe built strong communities around their cars. Whittier Boulevard and Crenshaw Boulevard became Californiaâ€™s main cruising strips, lined with polished Impalas, chrome spokes, and the sound of oldies and funk filling the air.
Artists like Mister Cartoon and photographers like Estevan Oriol captured that energy and helped carry the lowrider look into tattoos, fashion, and global art. Lowrider Magazine, founded in 1977, connected builders across the state and helped define the movementâ€™s visual identity.
After decades of police crackdowns and anti-cruising laws, California finally repealed those restrictions in 2023 with Assembly Bill 436, officially recognizing lowriding as part of the stateâ€™s cultural heritage. Today, Japan has its own lowrider scene inspired by Californiaâ€™s precision, creativity, and pride.
Lowriding is the story of working-class California â€” innovation, craftsmanship, and community built from the ground up.
